  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at the University of Southern Maine?",
  "response": "As someone who hasn't attended the University of Southern Maine, I cannot weigh in with any personal experience regarding the best small classes for freshmen. However, I can provide some general advice on how to identify small, engaging classes that might be a good fit for incoming students:\n\n1. **Check Class Size**: Look for courses with lower enrollment caps. Intro-level seminars or honors courses often have smaller class sizes.\n\n2. **First-Year Experience (FYE) Courses**: Many universities offer special classes designed for freshmen to help them transition to college life. These are often small and interactive.\n\n3. **Popular Freshman-Friendly Subjects**: Some introductory courses in subjects like psychology, sociology, creative writing, or environmental science tend to be smaller and more discussion-based.\n\n4. **Professors and Reviews**: Use resources like Rate My Professors or ask upperclassmen for recommendations on professors who are known for teaching engaging, approachable classes.\n\n5. **Advisor Recommendations**: Talk to your academic advisor. They often know which courses are well-suited for freshmen and which professors are particularly supportive.\n\n6. **Interest-Based Classes**: Choose a class in a subject you\u2019re passionate about. Smaller classes are often more common in specialized or niche areas.\n\n7. **Check the Catalog**: Review the course catalog for descriptions that emphasize discussion, collaboration, or hands-on learning\u2014these are often indicators of smaller classes.\n\nFor specific recommendations, it\u2019s best to consult with current students, academic advisors, or counselors at the University of Southern Maine who can provide insights tailored to your interests and goals.",
